-- Vedanta's India Power Unit Seeks 50,000 Tons of Coal a Month From Overseas
-- B y   P r a t i s h   N a r a y a n a n
-- 2010-12-16T04:58:48Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-16/vedanta-s-power-unit-seeks-50-000-tons-a-month-of-coal-update1-.html
Sterlite Energy, the power unit of
billionaire  Anil Agarwal ’s Vedanta Group, is seeking to import
50,000 metric tons a month of power-station coal for delivery in
2011, according to a notice in the Economic Times newspaper.  The Mumbai-based company, which is building two thermal
power plants in India with capacity totaling 5,040 megawatts,
wants to buy the coal from Indonesia or South Africa, the notice
shows. The tender is valid until Dec. 27.  Asia’s fastest-growing major economy after China is burning
more of the fuel as economic expansion boosts consumption. Coal
demand from India’s power industry may double by March 2017 from
450 million tons in the current financial year, Power Secretary
P.  Uma Shankar  said on Dec. 9.  More than half of the country’s current capacity of 167,278
megawatts is fueled by coal.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Pratish Narayanan  in Mumbai at 
 pnarayanan9@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
